@node intro "Introduction to concept"

@{u}Introduction@{uu}

	IconBar is a multipurpose toolbar.  The idea being that whatever you do on the mig you use lots of different apps - IconBar provides a graphical way of launching those apps and programs.

	So why did I write it?  Well, IconBar was originally "Internet ToolBar" because I wanted a toolbar that was workbench free (I don't have the memory to run Workbench so I just use a couple of shells) to do general internet type stuff - starting the stack, running email progs, irc, etc.  Workbench was too overkill and, well, you can't specify a drawer to open as default or, or...  and so on.  So I started looking for toolbars - loads of 'em everywhere.  Downloaded about 10 of the buggers and found NOT one that did this simple task.  Some were buggy, some were crap and needed MUI (missing the point totally) so finally I gave up and wrote what you see before you now.

	Being fair - the original net toolbar was a fair bit more primitive.  Major changes between net toolbar and iconbar have been rescalability (and a LOT of headaches to go with it!) which is a favourite feature of mine!  

	So enjoy - if it's any use I ask nothing more of you than to tell me it's of use.  Doing this will "inspire" me to write other Amiga stuff - and at the moment we need all the support we can get.

Best Wishes,

Ben Matthew.  (18/09/96)

@endnode

@node features "The lowdown on the main features..."

@{u}Features@{uu}

	* Resizability of all icons
	* Selection between unproportional bitmap scaling of icons and proportional
	* Window location and size can be snapshotted at the press of a key
	* Full icon tooltype support
	* Icons loaded in through datatypes - thus supporting all system file types
	* Loads itself into a custom process so it multitasks properly
	* Window title (or application "Base") can be changed to suit your application

@endnode

@node use "How to use and install IconBar"

@{u}Installation@{uu}

To set up IconBar do the following:
	1) Copy both the IconBar main program and it's icon to somewhere where you want to run it from.
	2) Load Workbench and edit the icons tooltypes
	3) Speicify the necessary settings by removing the brackets and specifing a value in the usual way -- see below for a detailed description
	4) Create two directories where the main prog is called "icons" and "scripts" - OR, copy the two directories in the archive with those namse to the same place as the main program
	5) Create a set (if doing your own bar) of images (which can be viewed with MULTIVIEW or similar) named 0-9 (or less if you want) and place them in the icons/ drawer
	6) Cretae a set of scripts to be executed when these icons are depressed.  Call thses scripts 0-9 respectively and place them in the scripts/ drawer

	NOTE THAT YOU DO NOT NEED TO DO STEPS 5 and 6 IF YOU ARE HAPPY WITH MY DEMO ICONS

	7) Run IconBar from wherever.

@{u}Using it - the fun part!@{uu}

	Ok so what does it do?  Well, after you have set it up and got it running, you can do the following things:

	a) Move it to where you want, pressing ANY key other than "P" will save the current window location and size
	b) You can resize the window - the icons will resclae with it
	c) YOu can speicify with the scaling on the icons should be in proportion or not by pressing the "P" key when the window is activated.  The window bar will adapt and scaling will change the next time you rescale

I recommened that you install the demo icons and scripts to see what they are doing, then modify them to suit your requirements and type of system.

Icon Preferences:

	The tooltypes you can change to set the preferences are:

	X = the default x position for the window (don't specify if you want the in-program snapping to work)
	Y = as x, but the y location
	WIDTH = width of the window by default (again it is recommended you do not specify this)
	HEIGHT = guess?
	SCALEMODE = default type of scaling - effectively what the p key does and hence it is like the x,y,w,h in the sense that you are best not to touch it here.  Set to 0 for unproportional or 1 for proportional.

@{b}
	BESTFIT = YES|NO, if this is set to yes then when the window is open, the program will calculate the best width of window to use for the set of icons you are using - to get the best representation hopefully.
	BASE = the basis of the application you want to put IconBar to.  Defaults to "Internet ToolBar" because I use it to launch net apps.
	IMAGES = the number of icons to render, 1-10
@{ub}

Command Line Args:

	Only one optional argument is supported - the number of images to render.  This corresponds to the IMAGES tooltype, i.e.:
	Shell.1> IconBar 3    (for three icons)
	Shell.1> IconBar 8    (for eight icons)
	Shell.1> IconBar      (for ten icons)

The icon tooltype will always out-precendent the command line arg.
	
@endnode

